<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-915  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 915.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 5 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UK: Computer Misuse Bill receives royal assent.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gold, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Great Britain. Computer Misuse Act 1990 (interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     LegislationComputer hackersComputer CrimesSecurityFraud.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UK: COMPUTER MISUSE BILL RECEIVES ROYAL ASSENT LONDON, ENGLAND, 1990 JUL 4(NB) -- After several readings in the lower and upper Houses of Parliament,the UK Computer Misuse Bill has received Royal assent.andP;  The granting of Royalassent means that the bill becomes a specific act under the UK legislature,and will become law in September.andM;The new laws make computer hacking - defined as the act of gainingunauthorized access to a computer system - an illegal action, punishable by afine and/or term in prison.andP;  Three new offenses are introduced.andM;According to David Frost, Price Waterhouse's management consulting partnerwith special responsibility for data security, &quot;the Act makes it clear thathacking and other computer-related crimes are being taken seriously and willbe severely punished.&quot;andM;&quot;While (the Act) addresses many of the problems of computer security, it isno substitute for thorough security procedures,&quot; he added.andM;The new Act, which comes into force in September of this year, tackles theproblems of unauthorized access, unauthorized access with intent andunauthorized modification to the contents of a computer.andP;  It also changes therules on jurisdiction to enable prosecution in cases of international fraud -UK courts can try cases if either the offender or the affected computer is inthe UK at the time of the alleged offense.andM;According to the annual Information Technology (IT) review by PriceWaterhouse, one of the UK's leading accounting firms and managementconsultants, only 20 percent of reported security incidents are due to theftor fraud.andP;  More than 76 percent are due to natural hazards, human error orsystem failure, although these do not, generally, have serious consequences.andM;The IT review also reveals that 65 percent of respondents from UK companieshave suffered to some extent financially, and seven percent have sufferedfrom &quot;major or crippling&quot; losses as a result of security failures.andM;(Steve Gold/19900704/Press andamp; Public Contact: David Frost, Price Waterhouse -Tel: 071-939-3000)</TEXT></DOC>